2. map()

Concept :
      map() is an intermediate operation used to transform each element of a stream into another form. It returns a new Stream containing the 
      transformed elements.
      
      Syntax:
      
      stream.map(element -> transformedElement)




1. Convert a list of strings into uppercase.
--> Program
          import java.util.Arrays;
          import java.util.List;
          
          public class UpperCaseExample {
              public static void main(String[] args) {
          
                  List<String> names = Arrays.asList(
                          "java", "spring", "react", "python");
          
                  names.stream()
                          .map(String::toUpperCase)
                          .forEach(System.out::println);
              }
          }
          Output
          JAVA
          SPRING
          REACT
          PYTHON





2. Given a list of integers, return a list of their squares.
--> Program :
        import java.util.Arrays;
        import java.util.List;
        
        public class SquareNumbers {
            public static void main(String[] args) {
        
                List<Integer> numbers = Arrays.asList(2, 3, 4, 5, 6);
        
                numbers.stream()
                        .map(n -> n * n)
                        .forEach(System.out::println);
            }
        }
        Output
        4
        9
        16
        25
        36




Program
    import java.util.Arrays;
    import java.util.List;
    
    class Employee {
    
        int id;
        String name;
        double salary;
    
        Employee(int id, String name, double salary) {
            this.id = id;
            this.name = name;
            this.salary = salary;
        }
    }
    
    public class EmployeeNames {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
    
            List<Employee> employees = Arrays.asList(
                    new Employee(101, "Ravi", 45000),
                    new Employee(102, "Anil", 60000),
                    new Employee(103, "Priya", 70000)
            );
    
            employees.stream()
                    .map(emp -> emp.name)
                    .forEach(System.out::println);
        }
    }
    Output
        Ravi
        Anil
        Priya
        
        Note: map() converts each Employee object into its name.




4. Convert a list of numbers into their string representation.
-->Program
      import java.util.Arrays;
      import java.util.List;
      
      public class NumberToString {
          public static void main(String[] args) {
      
              List<Integer> numbers = Arrays.asList(10, 20, 30, 40);
      
              numbers.stream()
                      .map(String::valueOf)
                      .forEach(System.out::println);
          }
      }
      Output
      10
      20
      30
      40
      
      Here, each Integer is converted into a String.




Summary :
| Question                     | Stream Method Used         | Transformation      |
| ---------------------------- | -------------------------- | ------------------- |
| Convert strings to uppercase | `map(String::toUpperCase)` | `String → String`   |
| Find squares of numbers      | `map(n -> n * n)`          | `Integer → Integer` |
| Extract employee names       | `map(emp -> emp.name)`     | `Employee → String` |
| Convert numbers to strings   | `map(String::valueOf)`     | `Integer → String`  |



Interview Tip :
    map() performs one-to-one transformation:
    
    Before map():
        [1, 2, 3, 4]
        
        map(n -> n * n)
    
    After map():
        [1, 4, 9, 16]
        
        Unlike filter(), which removes elements based on a condition, map() transforms every element into a new value.
